bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The Rockefeller Foundation was established by act of the New York State Legislature approved by the Governor on May 14, 1913, "to promote the well-being of mankind throughout the world." Between 1913 and 1928 the China Medical Board, the International Health Board, and the Division of Medical Education functioned as divisions of the Foundation, concentrating on the administration of programs in public health and medical education. A Division of Studies was created in 1923 to handle projects outside the medical field. These early years were experimental as the new foundation studied the methods of philanthropy and explored its relationships with other Rockefeller boards. Although the Rockefeller Foundation is the largest and best known philanthropy founded by the Rockefeller family, it was neither the first nor the last to be established. The Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research (1901), the General Education Board (1902), the Rockefeller Sanitary Commission for the Eradication of Hookworm Disease (1909), and the Bureau of Social Hygiene (1911) all existed earlier. When the Foundation was created, the Sanitary Commission was disbanded. After the establishment of the Foundation, the Laura Spelman Rockefeller Memorial (1918) and the International Education Board (1923) were created.

The Rockefeller boards and their programs were reconsidered and reorganized in 1927-1928 in order to avoid overlapping programs. The International Health Board of the Foundation was disbanded and an International Health Division was organized. The China Medical Board, Inc., was established as a separately incorporated institution, and the China Medical Board of the Foundation ceased to exist. The Division of Studies was dropped and the Division of Medical Education was phased out. The Laura Spelman Rockefeller Memorial was combined with the Foundation and the Spelman Fund of New York was chartered to continue activities of the LSRM that were not absorbed by the Foundation. The International Education Board was disbanded.

As a result of this reorganization, the Foundation adopted a program which included public health work (administered by the IHD), the advancement of knowledge in the medical and natural sciences (in part taken over from the IEB), the social sciences (formerly the field of the LSRM), and the humanities and arts (shared with the GEB). The Rockefeller Institute and the Bureau of Social Hygiene were not affected by the reorganization. The program adopted by the Foundation at this time remained basically the same for the next twenty years.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access note
accessrestrict.p: Records are open for scholarly research, with prior archival review. Retrieval time may exceed 24 hours.

RAC is unable to provide access to obsolete media and original digital media. In addition separated media may not yet have undergone stabilization procedures. When feasible, a digital surrogate may be created via special order. All applicable charges will apply. See RAC Head of Archival Services or RAC Head of Digital Programs for details.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: Rockefeller Foundation retains title, copyright and literary and intellectual property rights to the records, in so far as it holds them.
RAC has authority to grant permission to publish for scholarly purposes.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Standard processing was conducted by Gail Antos, Spring 2018. All records have been placed in acid free lignin free folders and rehoused in archival document storage boxes. Original order and original folder titles have been maintained.
This guide provides file level description. Each file may represent multiple folders.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged by the Rockefeller Foundation series (country code or series number) and subseries (program letter) structure.
Records are arranged as received. Within folders, materials are primarily arranged in reverse chronological order.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Open for research with select materials restricted as noted. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC. Researchers interested in accessing digital media (floppy disks, CDs, DVDs, etc.) or audiovisual material (audio cassettes, VHS, etc.) in this collection must use an access surrogate. The original items may not be accessed because of preservation concerns. To request an access surrogate be made, or if you are unsure if there is an access surrogate, please contact an archivist.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Standard processing was conducted by Gail Antos, Fall/Winter 2018. All records have been placed in acid free lignin free folders and rehoused in archival document storage boxes. Original order and original folder titles have been maintained.
This guide provides file level description. Each file may represent multiple folders.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Record Group 1.17 represents the period during which the Rockefeller Foundation transitioned from its traditional series (country code) and subseries (program letter) structure to a structure arranged by program only. The arrangement of the material in RG 1.17 reflects this transition.
Records are arranged as received. Within folders, materials are primarily arranged in reverse chronological order.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Open for research with select materials restricted as noted. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC. Researchers interested in accessing digital media (floppy disks, CDs, DVDs, etc.) or audiovisual material (audio cassettes, VHS, etc.) in this collection must use an access surrogate. The original items may not be accessed because of preservation concerns. To request an access surrogate be made, or if you are unsure if there is an access surrogate, please contact an archivist.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Standard processing was conducted by Gail Antos, Spring 2019. All records have been placed in acid free lignin free folders and rehoused in archival document storage boxes. Original order and original folder titles have been primarily maintained.
This guide provides file level description. Each file may represent multiple folders.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Record Group 1.18 is arranged by program. Records are arranged as received. Within folders, materials are primarily arranged in reverse chronological order.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Open for research with select materials restricted as noted. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC. Researchers interested in accessing digital media (floppy disks, CDs, DVDs, etc.) or audiovisual material (audio cassettes, VHS, etc.) in this collection must use an access surrogate. The original items may not be accessed because of preservation concerns. To request an access surrogate be made, or if you are unsure if there is an access surrogate, please contact an archivist.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Taped meeting at Rockefeller Foundation offices with choreographers Trisha Brown, Eliot Feld, and Paul Taylor. Brainstorming discussion about how to shape and develop a new RF choreographers program (Grant RF86006). Topics include: What should the grant criteria be?; Who should be funded?; What is the selection process?; Who should select?; Can a selector overcome personal bias?; Is selection subjective - or can it be objective?; How much should the funding amount be?; What is the grant trying to accomplish?; Where in the dance world is the need? Also, the choreographers discuss their methods of creation, as well as the difficulty of career continuity in dance. RF officers present (initials): ABA, HK, ESB, AAM.
